SpatialFin Privacy Policy

Effective: April 19th, 2026
Last updated: April 19th, 2026 (revised to describe the SpatialFin PIN mode, content-encryption feature, and wipe-on-wrong-PIN option)

This Privacy Policy applies to the SpatialFin application ("SpatialFin", "the App") published by Ignacio Martinez ("the Developer"). This is not legal advice; it describes how the App handles information.


1. SUMMARY

SpatialFin is a free, open-source Jellyfin client for Android. The Developer does not operate any backend server for the App, does not collect personal information, and does not use analytics, telemetry uploads, crash reporting, advertising identifiers, or any other form of tracking. Everything the App stores lives on your device, and everything the App transmits goes directly to services you have explicitly configured yourself.


2. INFORMATION COLLECTED BY THE DEVELOPER

None. The Developer has no servers, databases, analytics pipelines, or other infrastructure that receives data from the App. The Developer therefore does not collect, store, process, share, sell, rent, trade, or otherwise make use of any information from users of the App.


3. INFORMATION THE APP STORES LOCALLY ON YOUR DEVICE

The App stores the following data in Android's standard private application sandbox on your device. None of this is transmitted to the Developer:

  - Jellyfin server addresses, user accounts, and authentication tokens you provide.
  - API keys you provide for optional third-party services (e.g. TMDB, OMDb, Google Gemini, Jellyseerr).
  - User preferences (language, playback, display, voice, XR layout, and similar settings).
  - Cached images and metadata from your Jellyfin server.
  - Downloaded media you have explicitly chosen to download. When the optional content-encryption feature is enabled, newly finalized primary-video downloads are stored in AES-256-CTR ciphertext on disk; subtitle downloads and any downloads completed before you enabled encryption remain in plaintext. The per-download initialization vector is stored alongside the App's other database rows.
  - Optional local voice-command telemetry (latencies, command classifications) used only to render the in-app voice diagnostics screen.
  - Optional diagnostic log file in your device's Downloads folder, created only if you enable logging in settings.
  - Optional App-lock credentials:
    - In Biometric / device-credential mode, no App-managed secret is stored; the Android system holds the credential enrollment.
    - In SpatialFin-PIN mode, the App stores only a PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256 hash of the PIN together with a random salt and the corresponding key-derivation parameters. The PIN itself is never written to disk.
  - Optional encryption-key material: when content encryption is enabled, the App stores a 32-byte data-encryption key in encrypted form. The wrapping key lives in the Android Keystore (hardware-backed on capable devices) in Off and Biometric modes, and is derived directly from your PIN in SpatialFin-PIN mode.


4. THIRD-PARTY SERVICES YOU MAY CHOOSE TO ENABLE

The App can, at your option, communicate with third-party services. When you enable any of them, communication occurs directly between your device and that service under credentials you supply. The Developer is not a party to those exchanges and has no access to their contents. You are responsible for reviewing each service's own privacy policy and terms before enabling it.

  - Jellyfin server: the self-hosted media server whose address and credentials you provide. All library, metadata, streaming, and playback-state communication happens between your device and your Jellyfin server.
  - Jellyseerr / Overseerr: optional media-request integration.
  - The Movie Database (TMDB): optional metadata enrichment using a TMDB API key you supply.
  - OMDb (Open Movie Database): optional IMDb-backed ratings using an OMDb API key you supply.
  - Google Gemini / Generative Language API: optional cloud AI assistant fallback using a Gemini API key you supply. Voice prompts and the conversation context the App sends will be transmitted to Google under your own API credentials and subject to Google's privacy policy.
  - Companion hub: optional synchronization of preferences and bookmarks with another SpatialFin installation you control. Sync traffic travels over the local network or the endpoint you configure; it does not reach the Developer.

The Developer neither receives nor has access to your credentials, API keys, session tokens, or any data transmitted to these services.


5. ANDROID SYSTEM FEATURES INVOKED BY THE APP

The App uses standard Android platform features. Some of these are fully on-device; others may involve your device vendor's services outside the Developer's control.

  - Text-to-speech: the App uses the Android system TTS engine to read assistant replies. Some voices are marked "Network required" by the engine and, if you select one, the text to be spoken is transmitted to that engine's provider (typically Google). You can select a local-only voice from the voice picker in settings.
  - Speech recognition: when you invoke voice controls, the App uses the Android system SpeechRecognizer. Depending on the device and the recognizer implementation installed, audio may be processed entirely on-device or transmitted to the recognizer's provider (for example, Google).
  - On-device generative AI (AICore, Gemini Nano, LiteRT Gemma): when enabled, inference runs locally on supported devices. Prompts and outputs handled by these on-device engines are not transmitted outside your device by the App.
  - App lock (biometric, device credential, or SpatialFin PIN): when enabled in Biometric / device-credential mode, the App uses the Android BiometricPrompt API and the underlying biometric credentials are managed entirely by the Android system and are never accessible to the App. In SpatialFin-PIN mode, the App stores a PBKDF2-HMAC-SHA256 hash of the PIN and a random salt on the device, and the PIN also derives the key used to wrap the content-encryption key; the PIN itself is never written to disk and cannot be recovered.
  - Optional wipe-on-wrong-PIN: if you enable it, after the configured number of consecutive incorrect PIN entries (1–3) the App invokes Android's ActivityManager.clearApplicationUserData() and deletes the Downloads/SpatialFin folder. This is a local, irreversible operation performed entirely on your device; no data is transmitted anywhere as part of the wipe.
  - Media downloads: downloaded media is stored in your device's storage and is not transmitted anywhere by the App. When the optional content-encryption feature is enabled, newly completed primary-video downloads are written to disk as AES-256-CTR ciphertext and are decrypted in memory by the App's player at playback time.


6. ANDROID PERMISSIONS

The App requests Android permissions only for the corresponding in-app features, including but not limited to internet access, microphone access for voice controls, hand-tracking on XR devices, storage access for downloads, biometric authentication for App lock, and foreground service permissions for downloads and playback. Permissions are not used for any purpose other than operating the feature that requested them.


7. CHILDREN'S PRIVACY

The App is not directed to children under the age of 13 (or the equivalent minimum age in your jurisdiction, such as 16 under the European Union's General Data Protection Regulation). Because the Developer does not collect information from anyone, the Developer does not knowingly collect information from children.


8. INTERNATIONAL USERS

Because the Developer does not receive data from users, no cross-border transfer of personal data to the Developer occurs. Any cross-border transfers that may occur to third-party services you configure are governed by those services' own policies and legal frameworks.


9. SECURITY

Data stored by the App resides in Android's standard private application storage on your device. The App does not transmit this data to the Developer. The Developer does not warrant that your device or this storage is impenetrable. You are responsible for securing your device (screen lock, device encryption, operating-system updates, etc.).

The optional App-lock and content-encryption features are complementary to device-level security, not a replacement for it. Specifically:

  - App lock gates the App's user interface behind a biometric check or a SpatialFin PIN; it does not by itself encrypt any data on disk.
  - Content encryption, when enabled, encrypts newly completed primary-video downloads on disk with AES-256-CTR and wraps the content-encryption key with a Keystore-backed key (in Biometric / device-credential mode) or with a key derived from your PIN (in SpatialFin-PIN mode). Subtitles, streaming playback, the local database, and App preferences are not encrypted by this feature.
  - Forgetting your SpatialFin PIN is irreversible: the wrapping key cannot be recreated, so encrypted downloads become unrecoverable. If you enable wipe-on-wrong-PIN, repeated incorrect entries will additionally trigger a full local data wipe.
  - Neither feature protects against an attacker who obtains arbitrary code execution inside the App's process while the App is running and unlocked, nor against threats outside the scope of application-level mitigations. You are responsible for evaluating whether these features are appropriate for your threat model.


